        <p>There's a particular kind of exhaustion that comes from being the only adult in the house. You're managing everything — the kids, the logistics, the emotions, the finances — and there's no one to hand any of it off to. A support group doesn't solve those problems. But it puts you in a room (or a chat) with people who understand them without explanation, and that matters more than it sounds.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>On the resistance:</strong> most men don't love the idea of a support group. That's normal. If the phrase makes you picture a circle of chairs and a lot of crying, know that most dad groups are nothing like that — they're more like a regular conversation with people who get it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Types of groups</h2>

        <h3>Dad-specific groups</h3>
        <p>These are worth seeking out first — shared context makes a real difference. A room full of single dads means you don't have to explain why certain things are hard.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>City Dads Group</strong> — a national network of dad groups in 40+ cities. Originally for stay-at-home dads, but many chapters welcome single dads. <a href="https://citydadsgroup.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">citydadsgroup.com</a></li>
          <li><strong>National Fatherhood Initiative</strong> — runs fatherhood programs through community organizations, churches, and courts nationwide. <a href="https://www.fatherhood.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">fatherhood.org</a></li>
          <li><strong>Local courthouse or family law facilitator programs</strong> — many family courts run co-parenting and fatherhood support programs. Check your court's self-help center.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Online communities</h3>
        <p>Lower barrier to entry — no schedule to keep, no driving, available at 11pm when things get hard.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>r/SingleDads</strong> on Reddit — active community. Quality varies but there are real people there who've been through it.</li>
          <li><strong>r/daddit</strong> — broader dad community, more light-hearted, but single dads are well-represented and welcomed.</li>
          <li><strong>Facebook groups</strong> — search "single dads" + your city or state. Local groups often have meetups as well.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Divorce and co-parenting specific</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>DivorceCare</strong> — runs peer support groups through community organizations and churches in most U.S. cities. Designed for adults going through or recovering from divorce. <a href="https://www.divorcecare.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">divorcecare.org</a></li>
          <li><strong>DadsDivorce community</strong> — forums and resources specifically for fathers navigating divorce. <a href="https://www.dadsdivorce.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">dadsdivorce.com</a></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>General peer support</h3>
        <p>If there's nothing dad-specific nearby, a general peer support group is still worth it. NAMI (National Alliance on Mental Illness) runs free peer-led support groups in most areas — open to anyone, no diagnosis required. <a href="https://www.nami.org/Support-Education/Support-Groups" target="_blank" rel="noopener">nami.org/support-groups</a></p>

        <h2>How to find a group near you</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Search "[your city] single dad support group" or "[your city] fatherhood program"</li>
          <li>Call 211 (or text it) — it's a social services hotline that can connect you to local programs including fatherhood support</li>
          <li>Ask at your child's school — many schools have family resource coordinators who know local programs</li>
          <li>Check your county's Department of Social Services website — many fund fatherhood programs</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What to expect</h2>
        <p>A good group is mostly just people talking honestly about their situations. You don't have to share anything you're not ready to share. You can show up and listen for a while — that's fine and common. Most people find that within a few sessions, they're talking too.</p>
        <p>If a group doesn't feel right — bad fit, wrong vibe, not useful — try another one. Groups vary a lot based on who happens to be in them at a given time.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>The one thing almost everyone says:</strong> they waited too long to look for this. Whatever hesitation you have about it, it's worth trying once.</p>
        </div>

        <p>If what you need right now is professional help rather than peer support, the <a href="{{ '/mental/counseling/' | url }}">Counseling guide</a> covers how to find a therapist and how to afford it. If you're in crisis right now, go straight to the <a href="{{ '/mental/helplines/' | url }}">Helplines page</a>.</p>
